A fun take on the standard rogue-like genre, with skills and gear more fun 
to use than the boring, standard copy-and-paste most other games use. It 
isn't without it's faults, though; classes are very unbalanced, with archer 
and wizard being faceroll easy (powerful stamina efficient ranged attacks, 
low stamina, long distance movement skills, and strong AoE's), and others 
like Vampire relying almost wholly on luck (Vampire's untargetable teleport 
that costs stamina and HP, a very weak AoE, no ranged attacks, and their 
Thrall ability being almost completely useless). There's also a bug with 
the Alchemist's flask, where using one of the two charges will make any new 
potion you pick up only have one charge unless you empty your item slot 
completely before picking up a new one. It's also fairly short, and the 
town decorating thing is pointless. Overall a fun game, but could still use 
some polish, and some sort of endgame content after the story is completed. 
If you're a fan of the genre, you'll get your money's worth.

Want to clear one thing up first: this is an ACTUAL roguelike. Not a shmup with procedurally generated levels or whatever other nonsense people are calling roguelikes these days.  But it's not carefully balanced like a roguelike. Sure, there are cool moves like enemies that charge in a straight line across the entire playfield. But before long, you have abilities like rolling straight past an enemy that's blocking you. Or freezing enemies in a 9-square area with your BASIC attack. If you've played a roguelike or two, you know those moves are WAY overpowered, enough to take half of the strategy out of the game.  Oh, they attempt to balance it out. They added enemies that summon three allies each, or enemies that can't be killed unless you kill two halves simultaneously, or enemies that can teleport you away from the exit. But by the later levels, this just gets chaotic. You'll have enemies that you just roll through or run away from because you have no hope of killing them. Or you'll suddenly find yourself in a completely different part of the map, and you won't know why.  Would love to see this game redone with more traditional roguelike abilities.

replyContent: Sorry about that! You can fix it quickly in-game: click "+" on master volume in settings 10 times to get the console and enter 'unlockclass Wizard' (for example, if Wizard is the class in issue) in the console and hit enter. That'll fix it up for you. (capitalization matters)

replyContent:
You can get back to your previous stage by pressing + master volume in settings 10 times.

Type "stage " where x is the dungeon you had unlocked "stage 8", for example (without quotes), then press enter.

Sorry, it sounds like someone started a new game on your phone, which will overwrite the single save slot. Multiple slots are in the works.

I'm only giving four stars right now because I believe the game glitched when I unlocked the Vampire class. I got the message saying it was unlocked but it's never been playable. The classes feel very different and are a lot of fun to play, so I'm looking forward to unlocking the only one I haven't played as. All ten levels are fun and get plenty challenging, especially when those dang gold linked fish things pop up and appear immortal. Pleasantly puzzling and worth every minute.
replyContent:
Sorry about that! With the master volume at full, in settings hit the + master volume key 10 times to bring up the debug console.

Enter "unlockclass Vampire" without the quotes (and it's case sensitive, make sure the V is upper-case). Then clear the field and hit enter again in order to close the debug console.

You should be good to go, then!

replyContent: Sorry you're unhappy with the game! From your experience, it sounds like you are a skilled tactical gamer. I'd really implore you to try it out on Savage difficulty. In it, every monster has completely redesigned to be a real challenge to an experienced tactical gamer. I think you'll find the game you're looking for there, not on Normal!

It would be nice if MOGA controllers were also supported, but using my Moga Pro the only thing that worked was "A" to select things - no directional cues, nothing else. Perhaps that could be added later? Laugh, cry and die. Thanks for making it a game and not a watered down port!!!

As one of the original testers, I've played a ton of this game on PC and I'm really excited to have this game on mobile. The visuals are beautiful, and the gameplay is smooth (Galaxy S5 Cyanogenmod 11, Galaxy Tab Pro 12.2 Cyanogenmod 12). Winning requires thoughtful, tactical use of your class abilities and items, as well as learning strategies for all of the individual enemy-types. I've played alot of roguelikes and alot of this game, in particular, and savage mode is *still* tough. Dungeon playthroughs are the perfect duration for mobile at ~10-15 minutes per dungeon -- this is basically my ideal commuting game.

Its a great game! Love the fact that you also get to upgrade the town in between quests! However there are some things that make the game less fun. It appears to be that the poison jelly stacks and there is no way to see how much damage it would cause. For example if I kill 3 cute blue jellies in the same spot it would leave behind one blue tile, upon stepping on it I would take somewhere around 10 damage. Also I've spawned on the same spot as a next floor portal, so dungeon door placement could be better

Exactly what I've been looking for. Basically and HD roguelike, perfectly ported from PC with no IAPs. In a class with games like Dragonfall and X-Com for production value, and definitely worth the price of admission.
Excited for such a quality game. Artistically what I needed and mechanically what I've wanted.
